Analysis of Cycling Data¶

We are provided with four files containing recordings of cycling activities that include GPS location data as well as some measurements related to cycling performace like heart rate and power. The goal is to perform some exploration and analysis of this data.

The data represents four races. Two are time trials where the rider rides alone on a set course. Two are road races where the rider rides with a peleton. All were held on the same course but the road races include two laps where the time trials include just one.

Questions to explore with the data:

  • What is the overall distance travelled for each of the rides? What are the average speeds etc. Provide a summary for each ride.
  • Compare the range of speeds for each ride, are time trials faster than road races?
  • Compare the speeds achieved in the two time trials (three years apart). As well as looking at the averages, can you see where in the ride one or the other is faster.
  • From the elevation_gain field you can see whether the rider is climbing , descending or on the flat. Use this to calculate the average speeds in those three cases (climbing, flat or descending). Note that flat might not be zero elevation_gain but might allow for slight climbs and falls.

For time varying data like this it is often useful to smooth the data using eg. a rolling mean. You might want to experiment with smoothing in some of your analysis (not required but may be of interest).

Description of Fields¶

  • index is a datetime showing the time that the observation was made (I wasn't riding at night, this is converted to UTC)
  • latitude, longitude, elevation from the GPS, the position of the rider at each timepoint, elevation in m
  • temperature the current ambient temperature in degrees celcius
  • power the power being generated by the rider in Watts
  • cadence the rotational speed of the pedals in revolutions per minute
  • hr heart rate in beats per minute
  • elevation_gain the change in elevation in m between two observations
  • distance distance travelled between observations in km
  • speed speed measured in km/h

You are provided with code in gpxutils.py to read the GPX XML format files that are exported by cycling computers and applications. The sample files were exported from Strava and represent four races by Steve Cassidy.

Discrepancies¶

  • The elevation readings between the 2016 and 2019 rides differ.
  • Outliers exist within the 2019 road race power data.
  • Outliers exist within the 2016 time trial speed data.
  • Outliers exist within the 2016 time trial heart rate data.
  • The 2016 road race and 2019 road race start at slighlty different locations
  • The 2016 power data is missing (Steve must have got a power meter for christmas)
  • The 2016 time trail includes 4 initial observations where the subject is stationary, speed = 0 over 31 secs.
  • The 2019 time trial includes 9 initial observations where the subject may be stationary, power = 0, cadence = 0.

1.3 Data Cleaning¶

The data was adjusted to account for the above listed discrepancies as follows:

  • A moving average (data smoothing) was applied to the power, cadence, heart rate and speed attributes across all races to address outliers.
    • The window of 10 seconds was deemed appropriate.
    • As 2016 observations were taken at fluctuating intervals, the average time between intervals was calculated and used to find the number of observations required for the moving average.
  • To adrdress the large differences in elevation readings, the elevation was indexed to the minimum value for each ride.
  • The first 4 observations of the 2016 time trial data was dropped
  • The first 9 observations of the 2019 time trial data was dropped
  • Smoothing heart rate was not sufficient to remove outliers. It was estimated that a heart rate above 185 was an incorrect reading. All observations above 185 were reset to 185 bpm.

Hypothesis Test - One-way ANOVA¶

$H_0: \mu_{rr16} = \mu_{rr19} = \mu_{tt16} = \mu_{tt19}$

$H_1: \mu_i $ are not equal

In [24]:

Model Validation¶

Check for normality of residuals¶

In [27]:
residuals = model.resid
fig = sm.qqplot(residuals, line = 's')
plt.show()

The QQ-plot shows a slight right skew/heavy tail in the distribution of residuals however not significant. The normnality of residual assumptions holds.

Check for equal variance¶

In [28]:
r_16 = df['value'][df['variable'] == 'rr_2016']
r_19 = df['value'][df['variable'] == 'rr_2019'] 
t_16 = df['value'][df['variable'] == 'tt_2016'] 
t_19 = df['value'][df['variable'] == 'tt_2016'] 
ride_std = [r_16.std(),r_19.std(),t_16.std(), t_19.std()]
stdRatio = max(ride_std)/min(ride_std)
print(f'The ratio between the Max and Min standard deviations is: {stdRatio}')

The ratio between the Max and Min standard deviations is: 1.2393567003021557

The ratio between the max and min standard deviation values is less then 1.5. As such the variances between groups could be equal.

Conclusion¶

It was found that the 2016 road race had a significantly higher average speed when compared to the other three rides. The 2019 road race was not significantly different from the two time trials. From the result we are unable to conclude that one form of race is faster on average then the other.

1.7 Climbing/Descending Speeds¶

_From the elevation_gain field you can see whether the rider is climbing , descending or on the flat. Use this to calculate the average speeds in those three cases (climbing, flat or descending). Note that flat might not be zero elevationgain but might allow for slight climbs and falls.

The flat were defined as a gradient $> -2.5$% and $< 2.5$%

Climbs were defined as gradient $>= 2.5$%

Descents were defined as gradient $<= -2.5$%

In [35]:
#road race 2016
rr_2016_flat = rr_2016[((rr_2016['elevation_gain'] / (rr_2016['distance']*1000)) > -0.025) & ((rr_2016['elevation_gain'] / (rr_2016['distance']*1000)) < 0.025)]
rr_2016_clim = rr_2016[((rr_2016['elevation_gain'] / (rr_2016['distance']*1000)) >= 0.025)]
rr_2016_desc = rr_2016[((rr_2016['elevation_gain'] / (rr_2016['distance']*1000)) <= -0.025)]

tt_2019_flat = tt_2019[((tt_2019['elevation_gain'] / (tt_2019['distance']*1000)) > -0.025) & ((tt_2019['elevation_gain'] / (tt_2019['distance']*1000)) < 0.025)]
tt_2019_clim = tt_2019[((tt_2019['elevation_gain'] / (tt_2019['distance']*1000)) >= 0.025)]
tt_2019_desc = tt_2019[((tt_2019['elevation_gain'] / (tt_2019['distance']*1000)) <= -0.025)]

flat = pd.Series([rr_2016_flat['speed'].mean(), rr_2019_flat['speed'].mean(), tt_2016_flat['speed'].mean(), tt_2019_flat['speed'].mean()], index = raceType)
clim = pd.Series([rr_2016_clim['speed'].mean(), rr_2019_clim['speed'].mean(), tt_2016_clim['speed'].mean(), tt_2019_clim['speed'].mean()], index = raceType)
desc = pd.Series([rr_2016_desc['speed'].mean(), rr_2019_desc['speed'].mean(), tt_2016_desc['speed'].mean(), tt_2019_desc['speed'].mean()], index = raceType)


gradientSummary = pd.DataFrame({'Flat':flat, 'Climb': clim, 'Descent': desc}, index = raceType)
gradientSummary.round(2)

Observations¶

Across all three rides the subject was fastest on the descents and slowest on the climbs. It is possible that the average climbing speed is higher in road races then time trials. It is possible that the average flat and descending speeds are equal across the road race and time trial. The average descent speed could be greater in the 2016 road race then the 2019 road race. The average speed on the flats and descents could be greater in the 2019 time trial then the 2016 time trial. The average speed during climbs could be greater in the 2016 time trial then the 2019 time trial.

1.9 Challenge: Gear Usage¶

A modern race bike has up to 22 different gears with two chainrings on the front (attached to the pedals) and 10 or 11 at the back (attached to the wheel). The ratio of the number of teeth on the front and rear cogs determines the distance travelled with one revolution of the pedals (often called development, measured in metres). Low development is good for climbing hills while high development is for going fast downhill or in the final sprint.

We have a measure of the number of rotations of the pedals per minute (cadence) and a measure of speed. Using these two variables we should be able to derive a measure of development which would effectivly tell us which gear the rider was using at the time. Development will normally range between 2m and 10m. Due to errors in GPS and cadence measurements you will see many points outside this range and you should just discard them as outliers.

Write code to calculate development in meters for each row in a ride. Plot the result in a histogram and compare the plots for the four rides. Comment on what you observe in the histograms.
